  <a href="#1" id="1">
   New treatments that stop a heart attack in its tracks may help victims to get out of the hospital more quickly than ever before, perhaps even three days after their attacks, a study published today concludes.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Doctors from the University of Michigan Medical Center studied the effects of sending a few carefully selected heart patients home early.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   When given quickly after a heart attack, TPA can dissolve clots in the heart's arteries and minimize damage.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   In their paper, the doctors determined that 80 of the 507 heart attack patients studied were healthy enough to be considered for early discharge.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Gregory D. Curfman, a deputy editor of the journal, cautioned that the study was not large enough to spot complications that might result from reducing hospital stays.
  </a>
